description: A Bumblebee (Bombus sp.) pollinating the flowers of some Pride of Madeira (Echium candicans) at Lick Mill Park in Santa Clara, CA.  The presence of yellow hairs on the topmost abdominal segment (terga T1) eliminates the area's most common bumble bee - Bombus vosnesenskii - which always has black hairs across this part of its abdomen.  However, this opens the door to several other species, and exact identification would require a better view of the specimen, whose abdomen and face are partially concealed by the flowers that the bee is pollinating.  Therefore I am leaving this one identified to genus only.

Before seeing this one, I saw a smaller tortoise (as big as my hand) about 50 feet away! After admiring both tortoises, I continued my hike and on the way back, stopped to look for both tortoises and only saw the bigger one in its burrow. It was super neat to see :)

description: April 4th, 2019. 4:06pm. Mid 70’s. Small/young looking tortoise, as big as my hand. I watched it chew on dried/old/whiteish colored coyote scat. After admiring this one, I headed back on the trail, and saw another much larger tortoise, crossing the trail :) I was very lucky. This one was as big as a standard red ear slider turtle I would say, or like a teacup dish, or like my hand (I’m female). It was small. It was refreshing to see a small tortoise doing well out there :)
